snippet.textDisplay:
I thought 1 horsepower was about 3/4 the power of an average horse back when the measurement was first created back when the first steam engines were produced in order to make them appear a little better against the horse.
Edit; The info I found is from a Quora question answer so it may not be accurate but it says that the 1hp values came from the amount of work done by a draft horse in a day, it's the value that an average draft horse could be expected to perform at for a full day without wearing out the animal. A short burst of energy from a larger horse could be the equivalent to 15 to 20 hp, but it isn't sustainable. Likewise, it said that in a burst an average human could produce 5hp, but that's like sprinting 100 metres, you couldn't keep that pace for 8 hours on your feet.

snippet.textDisplay:
Horsepower was measured by donkeys, so yes a well bread horse could be 12 horsepowers.
Horsepower is power over time. If I remember right it was invented in the mines when they started using steam locomotives. They already knew how far a donkey could pull a cart in 1 minute, so that became 1 hp.
It should be called "donkeypower" or "asspower".
